  "prompt": "Do candles spoil?",
  "response": "Candles do not \"spoil\" in the same way that food does, but they can degrade over time, affecting their quality and performance. Here are some factors to consider:\n\n1. **Wax Quality**: Over time, the wax can become brittle or develop a whitish, powdery coating called \"bloom.\" This is more common in natural waxes like soy or beeswax. Bloom doesn't affect the candle's performance and can often be wiped off.\n\n2. **Fragrance**: The scent in scented candles can weaken over time, especially if the candle is stored in a warm or light-exposed area. To preserve the fragrance, store candles in a cool, dark place.\n\n3. **Wicks**: Wicks can become brittle or degrade over time, especially if the candle is stored in humid conditions. This can affect how the candle burns.\n\n4. **Container or Packaging**: If the candle is in a container, check for any cracks or damage to the container itself. Also, ensure that the packaging isn't compromised, which could expose the candle to dust or moisture.\n\n5. **Storage Conditions**: Ideal storage conditions include keeping candles in a cool, dry place away from direct sunlight and extreme temperatures. Proper storage can significantly extend the life of a candle.\n\n6. **Appearance**: If a candle has changed color or texture significantly, it might be a sign that it\u2019s past its prime. While it may still burn, the experience might not be as pleasant.\n\nIn summary, while candles don't spoil, their quality can diminish over time. Proper storage and care can help maintain their integrity for years.",
